‘ The archers of the vawarde were placed in the marish out-of daunger from the horsemen, yet for all that they did prevaile there somewhat, for the horsemen were appointed tono other purpose but to overrunne the archerS. The earle of Oxford, considering the discommoditie that might ensue thereos, departed from the prince’s warde, and leading with him the archers set them on the one side of the Frenchmen, commaunding them to shoote at the hinder parts of the horseS, by meanes whereof the horses being gauld and wounded fell to tumbling with them that sate on their backeS, or els turned backe and ran upon them that followed after, making great slaughter upon their owne masters, The horsemen being thus beaten backe, the archers retired towards the place from whence they came, shooting and gawling the sides of the Frenchmen which fought right over against them.
